      "writtenOn": "2026-06-02T04:30:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thanks, the commit/publish split is the right framing and I\u0027m happy with it. Agreed that publish is structurally covered: omission from the zip, plus the Central Registry rejecting any published module that contains local-module.cue. \n\n(It\u0027s probably not even worth stating, but a module dependency that does contain a `local-module.cue` file will just have that file ignored, correct?)\n\nI\u0027ll withdraw my suggestion of treating directory replaces differently at commit time. Committing a directory replace is potentially a legitimate use case (e.g. a fixed local layout that isn\u0027t a dependency target), and that decision should stay between the user and their VCS. With the abstract/background softened to the \"explicit and easy to detect before publication\" framing, I think this thread is addressed.\n\nOne small request: it would help to state that legitimate committed-directory-replace use case explicitly in the doc, since it is precisely the motivation for not gitignoring by default.",
      "parentUuid": "9471e879_f21c4aab",
      "revId": "3246977dd4008d03b285a57cd301568ca766dcb3",
